1 Introduction

Building a package in R can be a tedious venture, depending on the number of functions and the complexity of the whole package.

If the authorsâ intention is to make the package publicly available, the two standard repositories for R packages are:

  • CRAN (http://cran.r-project.org) and,

  • Bioconductor (http://www.bioconductor.org).

Helpful informations on all important steps of building an R package can be found in the R extension manual (http://cran.r-project.org/doc/manuals/R-exts.html).

Notice that, depending on the repository choice, the restrictions and the review process are different.

  • For Bioconductor the package guidelines are more rigorous than elsewhere and are available at: http://bioconductor.org/developers/package-guidelines/.
  • CRAN usually excepts packages that generally follow the R extension manual and that are not submitted as precompiled binaries (due to security reasons).

2 Getting started

To get started, make sure you also have the latest version of R (at least 3.5.0, which is the version that the code in this book uses), then run the following code to get the packages youâll need:

install.packages(c("devtools", "roxygen2", "testthat", "knitr"))

Make sure you have a recent version of RStudio. You can check you have the right version by running:

install.packages("rstudioapi")
rstudioapi::isAvailable("x.xx.xxx")

If not, you may need to install the preview version from http://www.rstudio.com/.

This gives you access to the latest and greatest features, and only slightly increases your chances of finding a bug.

Use the following code to access new devtools functions:

devtools::install_github("r-lib/devtools")

3 Package structure

A package is a convention for organizing files into directories. After writing some functions in your current R environment you can build a package automatically in R using the package.skeleton() function:

rm(list=ls())
package.skeleton("package_name")

or, we can create a new package project with:

devtools::create("path/package_name")

A folder named package_name should now be located in the current working directory.

3.1 Common structure of an R package:

3.2 Description of the most common parts of an R package

3.2.1 Setup DESCRIPTION file

  • DESCRIPTION [Required] : file with a description of the package, sets up how your package will work with other packages (dependencies), author(s) information, license, maintainer, etc.

3.2.2 Write code (R/ folder)

  • R/ [Required] : folder with the functions of the package. All of the R code in your package goes in this folder. A package with just and R/ directory is still a very useful package.

3.2.3 Tests

  • In tests/ [optional], we can store tests that will alert you if your code breaks.
  • Statements:
  • Example:
context("Arithmetic")

test_that("Math works", {
  expect_equal(1 + 1, 2)
  expect_equal(1 + 2, 3)
  expect_equal(1 + 3, 4)
})

3.2.4 man/ directory

  • man/ [Required] : contains the documentation for your functions, the help pages in your package.

3.2.5 data/ directory

  • data/ [optional] directory allows you to include data in your package. (Suggestion: Save data as .Rdata files).

3.2.6 NAMESPACE

  • NAMESPACE [Required] file helps you make your package selfcontained: making it accessible for other packages, and also for importing other packages or functions from other packages that are used insight this package.

3.2.7 README file

  • README: file with additional information about the package or changes since the last version of the package

3.3 Alternative:

By default, if you have at least one function and one R object in your current environment, the package.skeleton() function is creating the DESCRIPTION file and the folders R, man and data.

3.4 Hands on

Letâs create a very simple package myfirstpackage with two elementary functions. These functions calculate the confidence interval and a z.test for normal data with known variance. The functions are:

IC.z.test <- function(x, sigma, conf.level=0.95) {
  alpha <- 1 - conf.level
  z.alpha <- qnorm(1-alpha/2)
  n <- length(x)
  SE <- sigma/sqrt(n)
  return(mean(x) + c(-1,1)*z.alpha*SE)
}

z.test <- function(x, mu=0, sigma=1){
  n <- length(x)
  SE <- sigma/sqrt(n)
  z <- (mean(x)-mu)/SE
  p.value <- (1-pnorm(abs(z)))*2
  return(list(media=mean(x), z=z, p.valor=p.value))
}

package.skeleton("my_first_package")

Inspect contents (files and subfolders) of the generated package.

4 Package Files: Documentation

4.1 Documenting main files

4.1.1 The DESCRIPTION File

The DESCRIPTION file provides basic informations about the package (see http://cran.r-project.org/doc/manuals/R-exts.html#The-DESCRIPTION-file for information) and has in general the following structure:

Package: pkgname
Version: 0.5-1
Date: 2015-01-01
Title: My First Collection of Functions
Authors@R: c(person("Joe", "Developer", role = c("aut", "cre"),
                     email = "Joe.Developer@some.domain.net"),
              person("Pat", "Developer", role = "aut"),
              person("A.", "User", role = "ctb",
                     email = "A.User@whereever.net"))
Author: Joe Developer [aut, cre],
  Pat Developer [aut],
  A. User [ctb]
Maintainer: Joe Developer <Joe.Developer@some.domain.net>
Depends: R (>= 3.1.0), nlme
Suggests: MASS
Description: A (one paragraph) description of what
  the package does and why it may be useful.
License: GPL (>= 2)
URL: https://www.r-project.org, http://www.another.url
BugReports: https://pkgname.bugtracker.url
Notice that if the package is going to be submitted to Bioconductor, the additional field: biocViews: must includes keywords from the Bioconductor biocViews categories list (http://wiki.fhcrc.org/bioc/biocViews_categories) in order to be categorized into specific groups from the Bioconductor taxonomy.

4.1.2 The NAMESPACE File

R has a name space management system for packages. This system allows the package writer to specify which variables in the package should be exported to make them available to package users, and which variables should be imported from other packages (see http://cran.r-project.org/doc/manuals/R-exts.html#Package-name-spaces for details). A NAMESPACE file could look like this:

exportPattern("^[^\\.]")
import(packageA)
importFrom(packageB,functionInPackageB,anotherFunctionInPackageB)

  • The exportPattern line exports all functions from the R folder of the package, that do not start with a dot.

  • For importing other packages the import() lines imports the whole package and only loads it into the R environment if a function from that package is used in an R session. The importFrom() line only loads the specified functions.

  • Functions and packages can only be imported from a package A if that package A exports those functions in the NAMESPACE file of package A, otherwise that package has to be listed as a dependency in the DESCRIPTION file.

4.2 Documenting functions

The basic markup commands used for documenting R objects (in particular, functions) are given in this subsection:

\name{name}: name typically is the basename of the Rd file containing the documentation. It is the name of the Rd object represented by the file and has to be unique in a package. There can only be one entry in a file, and it must not contain any markup. Entries in the package manual will be in alphabetic order of the entries.

\alias{topic}: The sections specify all âtopicsâ the file documents. This information is collected into index data bases for lookup by the on-line (plain text and HTML) help systems.

\title{Title}: Title information for the Rd file. This should be capitalized and not end in a period; try to limit its length to at most 65 characters for widest compatibility. There must be one (and only one) \title section in a help file.

\description{.}: A short description of what the function do.

\usage{fun(arg1, arg2, .)}: One or more lines showing the synopsis of the function and variables documented in the file. These are set in typewriter font. This is an R-like command. The usage information specified should match the function definition exactly (such that automatic checking for consistency between code and documentation is possible).

For example:

\usage{
\method{print}{ts}(x, calendar, \dots)
}

which will print as

Usage:
     ## S3 method for class 'ts':
     print(x, calendar, ...)

  • \arguments{.}: Description of the functionâs arguments, using an entry of the form

  • \item{arg_i}{Description of arg_i.}: for each element of the argument list. General information about parameters.

  • \details{.}: A detailed if possible precise description of the functionality provided, extending the basic information in the slot.

  • \value{.}: Description of the functionâs return value.

  • \item{comp_i}{Description of comp_i.}: for each component of the list returned. Optional text may precede91 this list (see for example the help for rle). Note that is implicitly a environment, so that environment should not be used for listing components, just individual \item{}{} entries.

  • \references{.}: A section with references to the literature. Use or for web pointers.

  • \note{...}: Use this for a special note you want to have pointed out. Multiple sections are allowed, but might be confusing to the end users.

For example:

\note{
  Pie charts are a very bad way of displaying information.
  The eye is good at judging linear measures and bad at
  judging relative areas.
  ......
}

  • \author{.}: Information about the author(s) of the Rd file. Use \email{} without extra delimiters (such as â( )â or â< >â) to specify email addresses, or \url{} or \href{}{} for web pointers.

  • \seealso{.}: Pointers to related R objects, using \code{\link{...}} to refer to them (\code is the correct markup for R object names, and \link produces hyperlinks in output formats which support this. See Marking text, and Cross-references).

  • \examples{.}: Examples of how to use the function. Code in this section is set in typewriter font without reformatting and is run by example().

  • \keyword{key}: There can be zero or more \keyword sections per file. Each \keyword section should specify a single keyword.

4.3 Documenting datasets

The structure of Rd files which document R data sets is slightly different. Sections such as and are not needed but the format and source of the data should be explained.

Example:

\name{rivers}
\docType{data}
\alias{rivers}
\title{Lengths of Major North American Rivers}
\description{
  This data set gives the lengths (in miles) of 141 \quote{major}
  rivers in North America, as compiled by the US Geological
  Survey.
}
\usage{rivers}
\format{A vector containing 141 observations.}
\source{World Almanac and Book of Facts, 1975, page 406.}
\references{
  McNeil, D. R. (1977) \emph{Interactive Data Analysis}.
  New York: Wiley.
}
\keyword{datasets}

This uses the following additional markup commands.

  • \docType{.}: Indicates the âtypeâ of the documentation object. Always âdataâ for data sets, and âpackageâ for pkg-package.Rd overview files. Documentation for S4 methods and classes uses âmethodsâ (from promptMethods()) and âclassâ (from promptClass()).

  • \format{.}: A description of the format of the data set (as a vector, matrix, data frame, time series, .). For matrices and data frames this should give a description of each column, preferably as a list or table. See Lists and tables, for more information.

  • \source{.}: Details of the original source (a reference or URL, see Specifying URLs). In addition, section could give secondary sources and usages.

5 Installation and Checking

Basically, there are three statements available to process the package:

R CMD command packagename

where command should be:

  • check: runs a battery of tests on the package.

  • build: removes temporary files from the source tree of the package and packs everything into an archive file.

  • INSTALL: installs the package into a library and makes it available for usage in R.

All should be executed in the directory containing the source tree of the package.

5.1 Procedure

  • Step 1: R CMD check helps you do quality assurance on packages:

The directory structure and the format of DESCRIPTION are checked. The documentation is converted into text, HTML, and LATEX, and run through latex if available.

R CMD check "nom_package"

If any error or warning appears executing the âcheckâ statement, these should be fixed.

The âcheckâ statement creates a folder called .Rcheck containing the final structure of the package.

The âcheckâ statement also create the manual in PDF format.

  • Step 2: R CMD build will create a compressed package file from your package directory.
R CMD build "nom_package"

The âbuildâ process cannot produce error or warning either.

The build statement creates a (_.tar.gz) file, which is the one that has to be sent to publish.

  • Step 3: R CMD install installs the package into a library and makes it available for usage in R.
R CMD install "nom_package"

Packages can be submitted to CRAN by ftp. Make sure to run R CMD check with the latest version of R before submission. The CRAN maintainers will make sure that the package passes CMD check. Submit only the package sources, binaries are built automatically by designated platform maintainers.

5.2 Building and installing a package using devtools

You can then build and install the package from within R.

  • Step 1: Start R within your package directory (so that your package directory is Râs working directory).

  • Step 2: Install and load devtools by typing (within R)

install.packages("devtools")
library(devtools)
  • Step 3: Then, to check the package, type:
check("my_package")
  • Step 4: Then, to build the package, type
build("my_package")

Note: If your R working directory is something other than your package directory, you could specify the location of your package in the call to build.

  • Step 5: To install the R package, youâd type
install("my_package")

6 Publishing your R package

Make sure you are NOT violating any CRAN submission policies before you proceed (https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/policies.html).

  • Step 1: Go to CRAN website, http://cran.r-project.org/submit.html

  • Step 2: Fill in the basic details, upload the package and hit âUpload packageâ.

  • Step 3: It will take you to step 2, where you can verify the details and click Submit.
  • Notice that all maintainers of the package listed in description file, will get an email for confirmation. After maintainers confirm it, CRAN moderators will review it. If the package adheres to CRAN policies it should get approved.
